        title: "Common Mistakes in Policy Debates",
        content: "Even experienced debaters make predictable errors in policy rounds. Recognizing these patterns helps you avoid them and exploit them when opponents make them.\n\nThe first common mistake is a vague plan text. If your plan does not specify who does what, how much it costs, and how it is implemented, the negative will exploit every ambiguity. Write your plan text before the round and be prepared to defend every word of it.\n\nThe second mistake is weak solvency evidence. Many affirmatives prove the problem exists but fail to prove their specific plan solves it. The negative will argue that the plan is the wrong mechanism, too small to make a difference, or poorly designed. Your solvency evidence must directly connect your plan's mechanism to the problems you identified.\n\nThe third mistake is ignoring the negative's framework arguments. If the negative runs a kritik that challenges your underlying assumptions and you respond only with policy arguments, the judge may vote negative because you never engaged with their framework. Even if you think the kritik is wrong, you must explain why.\n\nThe fourth mistake is failing to extend arguments properly. In rebuttals, you cannot simply restate your original argument. You must extend it by answering the opponent's responses, adding new analysis, and explaining why your argument still stands despite their attacks.",
