        content: "External feedback from judges and peers is invaluable, but you cannot always have someone watching your performance. Learning to evaluate yourself objectively is one of the most important skills a debater can develop because it allows you to improve independently, between tournaments, and throughout your career.\n\nSelf-evaluation is harder than it sounds. We all have blind spots about our own performance. We tend to overestimate our strengths and underestimate our weaknesses. We remember the clever argument we made but forget the three points we dropped. We think our delivery was clear when it was actually rushed.\n\nThis lesson will teach you systematic methods for assessing your own performance honestly, identifying patterns in your strengths and weaknesses, and creating targeted improvement plans. The goal is to become your own best coach.",
