        title: "Recording and Reviewing Your Debates",
        content: "The single most effective self-evaluation tool is recording your debates and watching or listening to them afterward. The gap between how you think you performed and how you actually performed is almost always larger than you expect.\n\nWhen reviewing recordings, watch the full debate first without pausing or taking notes. Get an overall impression of how it flows. Then watch it again with a notepad, pausing at key moments to evaluate specific decisions.\n\nPay attention to things that are invisible in the moment: filler words like 'um' and 'uh,' pacing issues where you speed up under pressure, moments where you lose eye contact, or times when your organization falls apart. These habits are extremely difficult to notice while you are speaking but become obvious on recording.\n\nAlso notice what you do well. Self-evaluation is not just about finding flaws. Identify the moments where your delivery was compelling, your argument was sharp, or your refutation was devastating. Understanding your strengths helps you replicate them consistently rather than relying on them accidentally.\n\nIf video recording is not possible, audio recordings still provide valuable data about pacing, word choice, filler words, and argument structure. Even taking detailed notes immediately after a debate, while your memory is fresh, is better than nothing.",
