        title: "Identifying Cognitive Biases in Self-Evaluation",
        content: "Several cognitive biases systematically distort self-evaluation. Knowing about them helps you compensate.\n\nThe Dunning-Kruger effect means that people who are less skilled at something tend to overestimate their ability, while highly skilled people tend to underestimate theirs. If you are new to debate, you may rate yourself higher than warranted. If you are experienced, you may be too hard on yourself. Calibrate by comparing your self-evaluations with feedback from others.\n\nRecency bias causes you to evaluate your overall performance based on how the debate ended rather than the full round. If you gave a strong final rebuttal, you might rate the whole debate highly even if your constructive speech was weak. Force yourself to evaluate each speech separately.\n\nConfirmation bias leads you to notice evidence that supports your existing beliefs about yourself. If you think you are good at refutation, you will remember the times you refuted well and forget the times you missed key arguments. Actively look for evidence that contradicts your self-image.\n\nThe spotlight effect makes you think your mistakes were more noticeable than they actually were. That moment where you stumbled over a word probably went unnoticed by the judge, even though it felt catastrophic to you. Review recordings to get an accurate sense of how visible your mistakes really were.",
