        content: "The key to impromptu debate is not trying to prepare a complete case in your limited time. Instead, focus on establishing a framework and identifying two or three core arguments that you can develop during your speech.\n\nSpend the first 30 seconds understanding the resolution. Read it carefully, identify the key terms, and determine what the affirmative must prove. Many impromptu debaters waste time by misunderstanding the resolution and building arguments that do not actually address it.\n\nSpend the next minute brainstorming arguments for both sides. Write down every argument you can think of, no matter how rough. Do not evaluate them yet; just generate options. This brainstorm gives you raw material to work with.\n\nSpend the remaining time selecting your two or three strongest arguments and creating a brief outline. For each argument, write a one-sentence claim and note one example or piece of reasoning you can use to develop it. Do not write out full paragraphs; you will not have time to read them, and reading from a script sounds wooden.\n\nFinally, decide on your opening sentence and your closing sentence. Knowing how you will start and finish gives you confidence and structure, even if the middle is partially improvised.",
