        content: "When time is limited, having pre-built argumentation structures in your mental toolkit saves valuable seconds. These frameworks give you an instant skeleton to hang your arguments on.\n\nThe Past-Present-Future structure works for almost any topic. Analyze how the issue has been handled historically (past), what the current situation is (present), and what will happen if we adopt or reject the resolution (future). This structure is easy to remember and naturally creates a coherent narrative.\n\nThe Problem-Cause-Solution structure is ideal for policy-oriented impromptu topics. Identify the problem the resolution addresses, explain what causes the problem, and argue why the proposed solution (or the status quo) is better. This structure ensures you cover all the logical bases.\n\nThe Criteria-Application structure works well for value-based impromptu topics. First, establish the criteria by which the resolution should be evaluated (such as fairness, effectiveness, or freedom). Then apply those criteria to show that your position meets them better than the alternative.\n\nThe Comparison structure works when you can draw a clear parallel. Compare the situation in the resolution to a similar situation where the outcome is known. If you can show the cases are analogous, the known outcome strengthens your argument about the unknown one.\n\nHaving these four structures memorized means you always have a starting point, no matter what topic you receive.",
